es enormous effects which are highly decentralized and beyond the reach of state power. Third, the Internet has created a new infrastructure for the state and society in their engagement with (and disengagement from) each other. Fourth, the Internet produces a recursive relationship between state and society. The interactions between the state and society over the Internet end up reshaping both the state and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362681240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626812/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles